  "final_prompt": "CountGD tuning notes (updated):\n\n- High-confidence successful adjustments:\n  - \"count the individual bright spots or blobs in the image\" \u2014 helped 19/19 tried (strong performer across low-contrast, sparse, noisy images; now the most reliable prompt across all image types)\n  - \"count the individual bright spots or particles in the image\" \u2014 helped 12/12 tried (robust for star-like, low-contrast objects; still effective but less universally reliable than the above)\n  - \"count the bright, out-of-focus circular spots that resemble cells\" \u2014 helped 3/3 tried (effective for ambiguous, faint, cellular-like features; remains useful when morphology is unclear)\n  - \"count the individual cells in the image, including faint and overlapping ones\" \u2014 helped 9/9 tried (new high-confidence addition; effective for overlapping, faint, or clustered structures; now preferred over vague \u201ccells\u201d phrasing when morphology is ambiguous)\n  - \"count the individual cells in the image, including those that appear blurred or overlapping\" \u2014 helped 13/13 tried (new high-confidence addition; robust for low-contrast, clustered, or noisy fields; now recommended for ambiguous or crowded scenes)\n  \u2192 These phrasings consistently improve performance on low-contrast, sparse, noisy images with minimal context. Prioritize \u201cbright spots or blobs\u201d for maximum reliability. For ambiguous or clustered morphology, use \u201cfaint and overlapping\u201d or \u201cblurred or overlapping\u201d variants. For partial occlusion or vague shape, use \u201cblurred or partially obscured\u201d or \u201coverlapping or clustered shapes\u201d \u2014 but only if morphology is clearly cell-like.\n\n- Low-confidence or ineffective adjustments:\n  - \"count the bright, out-of-focus circular spots in the dark blue background\" \u2014 helped 1/1 tried (narrow context; only reliable if background is clearly dark blue + out-of-focus; use only if image context is explicitly defined)\n  - \"count the bright, out-of-focus circular objects in the bottom-right corner of the image\" \u2014 helped 1/1 tried (too specific; may not generalize; avoid unless region is clearly bounded)\n  - \"count the individual cells in the image, including faint and blurry ones\" \u2014 helped 2/2 tried (ambiguous; \u201ccells\u201d may confuse model when morphology is unclear; use only if morphology is clearly cell-like and unambiguous)\n  - \"count the individual blue circular cells\" \u2014 helped 1/1 tried (too specific; only reliable if color is a defining feature; low-confidence due to narrow context)\n  \u2192 These are contextually precise but lack robustness. Use only if image context is clearly defined (e.g., dark blue background, specific region, or color is a defining morphological feature).\n\n- High-scoring output characteristics (when no ground truth):\n  - Perfect score (0 MAE) often occurs when:\n    - Image is nearly empty or contains only one faint, barely visible spot \u2014 model predicts 0 objects (plausible if visual evidence is extremely weak or ambiguous)\n    - Image contains 1\u20135 clearly defined, well-separated, high-contrast objects \u2014 model reliably detects and localizes them with minimal overlap or misalignment\n  - High scores (0.6\u20130.7+) typically co-occur with:\n    - Moderate to high contrast between objects and background\n    - Sparse to moderately dense object distribution (avoiding extreme crowding)\n    - Well-defined, non-overlapping or minimally overlapping object boundaries\n    - Minimal background noise or artifacts (e.g., air bubbles, tissue folds)\n    - Objects that are circular, round, or have clear edges (even if faint)\n  - Low scores (0.3\u20130.4 or below) typically co-occur with:\n    - Low contrast, noisy, or textured backgrounds\n    - Sparse, faint, or irregular",
